resent a variety of disciplines, not only in respect to their individual fields of inquiry, but with respect to the study of music itself, embracing musicology and ethnomusicology, historical and systematic research, philology and hermeneutics. The general and particular legacy of the ancient classics as a stable element in music discourse is a common thread that binds the essays together.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEditingvCongresses. 0aMusic theoryvEarly works to 1800xTranslatingvCongresses. 0aMusicxHistory and criticismvEarly works to 1800xTranslatingvCongresses. 0aMusicologyvCongresses. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Translating & Interpreting.2bisacsh1 aBowen, Alan C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowen, William R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrier, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreyszig, Walter Kurt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManiates, Maria Rika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPalisca, Claude V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSawa, George Dimitri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267746340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442677463423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442677463.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  